08361nam a22009855i 9783866539907DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97838665399077 a10.1515/97838665399072doi  a(DE-B1597)212976  a(OCoLC)979598113  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAW0000002bisacsh0481xa346.24  aPS 37302rvk0(DE-625)rvk/139785:04aThe Making of European Private Law: Why, How, What, Who /ced. by Luigi Moccia. 1aMunich : bOtto Schmidt/De Gruyter european law pub, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (225 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tForeword -- tList of Authors -- tTable of Contents -- tEuropean Private Law: Why, How, What and Who? -- tThe Europeanisation of Private Law: Problems and Perspectives -- tThe Commission Proposal for a “Regulation on a Common European Sales Law (CESL)” – Too Broad or not Broad Enough? -- tThe ‘Legal Basis’ of European Private Law in the Light of EU Constitutionalisation -- tEuropean Law: From ‘Market’ to ‘Citizenship’ -- tA Common European Sales Law (CESL) for Business-to-Business Contracts -- tThe ‘Instruments’ for Implementing European Private Law – The Influence of the ECJ Case Law on the Development and Formation of European Private Law -- tOptional Law for Firms and Consumers: Economic Benefits of Opting into the Common European Sales Law? -- tEuropean Consumer Law and its Consolidation -- tThe Internal Relationships of EU Consumer Contract Laws: Unfair Contract Terms, Unfair Commercial Practices and CESL -- tEuropean Property Law – Transfer of Ownership of Movables -- tFrom Euratom Property Law to European Union Property Law: A Concise Overview of the Development Towards a European Property Law -- tWhich Future for the European Law of Successions? -- tInterpretation of Contracts in European Private Law -- tIncorporation and Unfairness of Standard Contract Terms Under the Proposal for a Common European Sales Law -- tThe Application of the CESL to a Contract for the Supply of Digital Content (e.g. Software) -- tA Critical First Glance at the Common European Sales Law Project by the Digital Consumer Law Approach0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter Lisbon, European integration has moved towards new and more ambitious objectives, with the aim of strengthening the Union’s institutional architecture as well as rationalising and legitimising its legal order.Within this broad context, the making of European private law is a challenge that faces basic questions, such as:"Why European private law is needed?","How European private law could and should be set up?","What areas, to what extent and what policy objectives could and should be involved?" and"Who carries the responsibility of making it?".The book, through a variety of thematic contributions, offers several *nsights for a wide-ranging reflection on such issues, together with a more specific analysis of the most recent Commission’s proposal for a regulation on a "Common European Sales Law" (CESL).  aDie Vorbereitungen laufen bereits viele Jahre, nun liegt er endlich vor: der Entwurf der Europäischen Kommission für ein Gemeinsames Europäisches Kaufrecht als Optionales Instrument. Beteiligte an den Vorarbeiten und wichtige Kritiker derselben setzen sich in diesem höchst empfehlenswerten Buch mit dem Kommissionsentwurf auseinander. Wie wird die Harmonisierung des europäischen Vertragsrechts durch den Entwurf vorangetrieben? Wie "schlägt" sich der Entwurf im Vergleich zum BGB, zum DCFR oder zu den Acquis-Principles? Beleuchtet werden insbesondere Irrtumsanfechtung, AGB-Kontrolle, allgemeines und besonderes Leistungsstörungsrecht beim Kauf und bei verbundenen Dienstleistungen sowie übergreifende Fragestellungen zum Verbraucherrecht. Der Band wird abgerundet durch eine Synopse des Kommissionsentwurfs und der vorangegangenen Machbarkeitsstudie, in der die Entwicklung des Textes deutlich wird.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil lawzEuropean Union countriesvCongresses. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aBeale, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalliano, Oreste M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClive, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErp, Sjef van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFauvarque-Cosson, Bénédicte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanuza, Juan José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGomez, Fernando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrynbaum, Luc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLando, Ole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoos, Marco B.M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLurger, Brigitta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMicklitz, Hans-Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoccia, Luigi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoccia, Luigi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPisuliński, Jerzy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReich, Norbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTraisci, Francesco Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTrstenjak, Verica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWendehorst, Christiane C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhittaker, Simon, econtri